This is a list of places below mean [sea level](/wiki/Sea_level "Sea level")
that are on land.

Places in tunnels, mines, basements, dug holes (also with open sky), under
water, under ice, or existing temporarily as a result of ebbing of sea tide
etc. are not included. Places where seawater and rainwater is pumped away are
included. Fully natural places below sea level require a dry climate;
otherwise, rain would exceed [evaporation](/wiki/Evaporation "Evaporation")
and fill the area.

All figures are in meters below sea level, arranged by depth, lowest first:

## Historic and ice-covered
areas[[edit](/w/index.php?title=List_of_places_on_land_with_elevations_below_sea_level&action=edit&section=8
"Edit section: Historic and ice-covered areas")]

Deeper and larger than any of the trenches in the list above is the [Bentley
Subglacial Trench](/wiki/Bentley_Subglacial_Trench "Bentley Subglacial
Trench") in Antarctica, at a depth of 2,540 m (8,330 ft). It is subglacial,
meaning that it is permanently covered by the largest ice cap in the world.
Therefore, it is not included in any list on the page. If the ice melted it
would be covered by sea.

The biggest dry land area below sea level that has been known to exist in the
geological past, as measured by continuous volume of atmospheric air below sea
level, was the dry bed of the [Mediterranean Sea](/wiki/Mediterranean_Sea
"Mediterranean Sea") in the late [Miocene period](/wiki/Miocene_period
"Miocene period") during the [Messinian salinity
crisis](/wiki/Messinian_salinity_crisis "Messinian salinity crisis").
